      "description": "The Zildjian Z Custom cymbal setup Herrera used on *Obsolete* was unchanged from his *Demanufacture* configuration — the same series chosen for the same reasons: upper-frequency brightness that places cymbal frequencies above the dense guitar wall of industrial metal, and the physical durability to withstand sustained high-impact touring.\n\nFor *Obsolete*, the Z Custom's brightness served a specific function in Rhys Fulber's production. Fulber's background in electronic music made him acutely aware of frequency competition in a dense mix — down-tuned guitars, industrial electronics, and heavy bass all competing for low and mid frequencies. The Z Custom's upper-frequency emphasis meant cymbals could project clearly through the mix without Fulber needing to artificially boost high frequencies in post-production.\n\nThe china cymbal receives particular emphasis on *Obsolete*. \"Edgecrusher,\" \"Shock,\" and \"Smasher/Devourer\" all feature prominent china cymbal accents that drive the tracks' most intense sections. The Z Custom China's aggressive, trashy character — its inverted bell and curved edges creating a distinctive crash quality distinct from standard crashes — provided exactly the kind of emphatic accent marker that Fear Factory's structured, riff-based compositions required.\n\nFulber's production captured the Z Custom cymbals with enough definition to distinguish between the different cymbal voices — the hi-hat's cutting pulse, the crash's explosive accent, the china's aggressive trash — rather than letting them blend into an undifferentiated high-frequency wash. This clarity of cymbal definition is one of *Obsolete*'s production strengths.",
